<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="392" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,577,965]" pageId="4" pageNumber="392">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,577,603]" pageId="4" pageNumber="392">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Large-sized, male body longer than 
<quantity box="[679,760,578,605]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="392" unit="mm" value="35.0">35 mm</quantity>
. Vertex of head narrower and somewhat equal to the distance between eyes; posterior pronotal collar broad; broad pale transverse band across the postclypeus; lateral margin of pronotum dentate. Wings hyaline; forewing basal vein of apical cell 1 extremely short; forewing apex sharp; costal margin of forewing hardly concave. Metanotum entirely concealed at midline. Male opercula small, scale-like, wider than long, and nearly contiguous to each other. Larger part of the timbal concealed with timbal covering. Male abdomen gradually tapering to apex; lateral surfaces of 3rd and 4th abdominal sterna without tubercle-like projections; 8th abdominal tergum with no or little white pollinosity; lateral pygofer lobes acute; a trapezoid uncus with a medial incision suggesting the fusion of two short &amp; broad lobes; a pair of claspers with each with two spines protruding from below the uncus; distinctly protruding paramedian basal pygofer lobes or basal pygofer lobes that are placed laterally adjacent to the sides of the pygofer (
<bibRefCitation author="Distant, W. L." box="[793,956,902,928]" pageId="4" pageNumber="392" refId="ref9538" refString="Distant, W. L. (1906 a) The fauna of British India, Including Ceylon and Burma. Rhynchota. Vol. III. Heteroptera-Homoptera. Taylor and Francis, London, 526 pp." type="book" year="1906">Distant 1906a</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Lee, Y. J. &amp; Hayashi, M." box="[969,1209,902,928]" pageId="4" pageNumber="392" pagination="359 - 392" refId="ref10065" refString="Lee, Y. J. &amp; Hayashi, M. (2003) Taxonomic Review of Cicadidae (Hemiptera, Auchenorrhyncha) from Taiwan, Part 2. Dundubiini (A Part of Cicadina) with Two New Species. Insecta Koreana, 20, 359 - 392." type="journal article" year="2003">Lee &amp; Hayashi 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Duffels, J. P. &amp; Hayashi, M." pageId="4" pageNumber="392" pagination="189 - 201" refId="ref9703" refString="Duffels, J. P. &amp; Hayashi, M. (2006) On the identity of the cicada species Pomponia picta (Walker) (= P. fusca (Olivier )) and P. linearis (Walker) (Hemiptera, Cicadidae). Tijdschrift voor Entomologie, 149, 189 - 201. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 22119434 - 900000198" type="journal article" year="2006">Duffels &amp; Hayashi 2006</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Pham, T. &amp; Lee, Y. J. &amp; Constant, J." box="[221,416,938,965]" pageId="4" pageNumber="392" pagination="562 - 572" refId="ref10273" refString="Pham, T., Lee, Y. J. &amp; Constant, J. (2015) Cicada genus Pomponia Stal, 1866 (Hemiptera: Cicadidae) from Vietnam and Cambodia, with a new species, a new record, and a key to the species. Zootaxa, 3925 (4), 562 - 572. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3925.4.5" type="journal article" year="2015">
